 socialism, devoid of its Christian elements. According to Biemann, the phenomenon of Jewish self-recognition in Michelangelo's work offered an alternative to the failed promises of the German enlightenment. Through this unexpected discovery, he rethinks German Jewish history and its connections to Italy, the Mediterranean, and the art of the Renaissance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aJewish aestheticszGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewish aestheticszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszGermanyxIntellectual lifey19th century. 0aJewszGermanyxIntellectual lifey20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478436840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804784368423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804784368.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles